body:
It turns out that it isn't (for now). It's isn't generally possible to make it thread safe given that people can replace the module dict with arbitrary mappings, but we can at least handle the common sensible case where it's a dict.

I'm mostly concerned with the shared utility module here.

comment_data.body: I've spotted a few places elsewhere where we assume that `PyImport_GetModuleDict` really does return an exact dict. Which turns out not to be completely true but I didn't convince myself to fix right now
We could try if it has a `setdefault` method and call that? But yeah, it seems a rare case, not necessarily worth bothering.

It also doesn't necessarily help - the thread safety is specific property of `PyDict_SetDefault` and not `setdefault` in general. (It certainly isn't for the generic implementation in `collections.abc.MutableMapping`)

I was thinking that it would at least give users a path to make it work, by fixing their `setdefault` implementation.
Anyway, since CPython has the same problem internally, there will eventually be an example to follow. Or not.

There's at least some possibility that you can't actually end up with non-dicts here (https://github.com/python/cpython/issues/137422#issuecomment-3160010347) although CPython still tries to handle non-dicts so there's clearly a bit of confusion.

I think I tried to follow the logic at the time and think I agreed with the conclusion but it was hard to be absolutely sure.

commit.message:
Make "PyImport_AddModuleRef" somewhat thread safe

It turns out that it isn't (for now). It's isn't generally
possible to make it thread safe given that people can replace the
module dict with arbitrary mappings, but we can at least handle the
common sensible case where it's a dict.

I'm mostly concerned with the shared utility module here.
